Common Js VS ES module
require -> CommonJS
import -> ES Module

Node Js is default to commonJS

Common JS 
- Older
- Node-native (Node uses it by Default)
- Most backend trainings use this.

ES Modules
- Modern JavaScript
- Browser Standard
- Cleaner/Beautiful Syntax
- Needs Configuration (type=module in package.json file)

Async/Await
=============
- If you're using.function, we can't await without the method being async 
- if a function is async, you need to await the function if you're using somewhere else

async function getUsers(){
    return // reading 1 million data from json file
}

const fetchUsers = await getUsers(); // some seconds
console.log(fetchUsers)

async function updateUser(userId){
    const allUsers = await getUsers();
}


/////////////////////////
JWT - JSON Web Token

JSON - DAta Format
Web - Used in HTTP
TOKEN - Proof of Identity

JWT Structure
==============
It has 3 sections separated by DOTS (.) HEADER.PAYLOAD.SIGNATURE
1. Header - Algo, typ { "algo": "HS256", "typ": "JWT"}
2. Payload - Actual Data you're sending for the server to know who this is. 
{
  "id": 7761,
  "email": "vatif@mailinator.com",
  "user_type": "vendor",
  "status": "incomplete",
  "tokenVersion": 0,
  "iat": 1770233788,
  "exp": 1770838588
} // Never put password

3. Signature - The most IMPORTANT (SECRET) - Always in your ENV file 